<p>Source: USDA, ‘Swaziland: Sugar Annual’, <i>GAIN Report</i>, 17 April 2013 (drawn from Tables 1 and 3)</p><p>USDA reports that since 2000/01, the area under sugar in Swaziland has increased by 28%, with sugar cane production increasing by 30%. A further 10% increase in sugar cane production is projected through to 2016/17, bringing production to 6.5 million tonnes.</p><p>Swaziland enjoys a 14.1% share of the official SACU sugar market (i.e. combined recorded sales and imports), having consistently supplied over 300,000 tonnes to the SACU market over the past 10 years.</p><p>In recent years, however, Swaziland has been exporting more sugar to the EU than to the SACU market. This reflects the importance of the granting of unrestricted duty-free, quota-free access to the EU sugar market under the interim EPA arrangement. The higher returns available on the EU market have meant that in recent years Swaziland has not taken up its quota on the US market.</p><p>While Swaziland exports mainly raw sugar, refined sugar exports increased by 50% in 2012/13, with a further 11% increase projected for 2013/14. However, by 2013/14 refined sugar exports are still projected to account for only 13.9% of total sugar exports.</p><p>Later in April, the Mozambican news agency, citing the government’s Centre for the Promotion of Agriculture (CEPAGRI), reported that Mozambican sugar exports increased by 23% in 2012, from 198,181 to 243,583 tonnes. These exports are destined exclusively for the EU.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘Swaziland: Sugar annual’, <i>GAIN Report</i>, 17 April 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Sugar%20Annual_Pretoria_Swaziland_4-17-2013.pdf " target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Sugar%20Annual_Pre...</a></p><p>Agencia de Informação de Moçambique (AIM), ‘Mozambique: Sugar exports reach record levels’, 24 April 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201304300974.html " target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201304300974.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In the specific context of Swaziland, the EU now accounts not only for a higher value of Swazi sugar sales, but also for a higher volume of sugar sales than the SACU market. Indeed, compared to the access granted under the earlier EU Sugar Protocol and special preferential sugar arrangements, Swaziland has doubled the volume of its sugar exports to the EU, eliminating sales to the generally lower-priced world markets.</p><p>As a result of the increased volume of exports to the EU, with EU sugar prices in recent years being supported by policy-induced shortages of sugar on the EU market, the Swazi sugar sector has been little affected to date by reductions in the EU guaranteed price for ACP sugar.</p><p>Taken together, Swaziland and Mozambique now account for around 31% of EU imports of sugar from ACP/LDC countries, up from around 10% under the previous quota-limited access arrangements.</p><p>Taking into account similar trends in the expansion of the production and export of sugar in Zambia, Malawi and Zimbabwe, Southern Africa is becoming the dominant ACP/LDC supplying region, accounting for 52% of ACP/LDC sugar supplies. This compares to a 16.1% share of ACP/LDC sugar exports during the period of quota-restricted market access arrangements in place prior to EU sugar sector reform.</p><p>It is thus Southern Africa countries that will be most impacted by the market consequences of EU sugar quota abolition (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/EC-projections-of-EU-sugar-market-developments-after-the-expiry-of-the-production-quota-system" target="_blank">EC projections of EU sugar market developments after the expiry of the p...</a>’, 6 February 2012). This will increase the importance of issues related to the functioning of sugar supply chains, both at the international level and internally, in terms of the sharing of revenues from cane-based non-sugar income streams with sugar cane producers (for details on internal EU discussions on strengthening the functioning of supply chains, see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/CAP-reform/Report-on-improving-functioning-of-food-supply-chain-released" target="_blank">Report on improving functioning of food supply chain released</a>’, 11 March 2013).</p><p>This constitutes an important new policy agenda for governments and sugar farmers’ organisations across the Southern African region.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
